OK - I waited for a year after experiencing the exact same problem as most of you. At that time, I let chkdsk continue even though it worked for over four hours doing strange things with the 180gb on my 250gb NTFS formatted OS drive. The cause was a stupid mistake on my part -- no, THREE stupid mistakes! I over-confidently tried to upgrade my XP-SP2 to SP3 before it was fully proven, and I could not reboot, not even into Safe Mode. Althouth the OS was crapped, all my valuable files and reports were intact and could have been backed up using my laptop and a USB external drive (no. 2 mistake). I used an old 80gb drive, wiped clean, and loaded my old XP onto it; then plugged my problem drive in as secondary, hoping to remove the OS so I could start (no. 3 mistake). My version of XP was before SP2 so it couldn't recognize my larger 250gb drive -- so it ran chkdsk.
Last week, I bit the bullet and plugged the problem disk in as secondary, once again, but with XP-SP3 fully installed and well tested. I booted into Safe Mode with command line and ran chkdsk /f. After about three hours I was able to pull my files out of about 500 chkdsk files which contained familiar sub-directories and myriad isolated files. So far, I've only found a few incomplete picture files, but my videos, reports, and research files appear to be saved.
I owe the success of this operation to everyone of you who walked onto this battlefield and especially Janos, who resolutely kept this forum intact and available. I also admonish Microsoft for failing us by not offering much advice at all, no wisdom, no easily available XP install disk with all updates and no cautions about what might happen in such a case.
Thank you all!

What a find!! I consider myself very fortunate to have found this forum, albeit through the screen of my wife’s laptop. The story goes a lot like this.

My machine was busy viscously throwing line after line of script toward the ceiling! Yes, yes the worrisome “Inserting an index entry into index $0 of file 25”. I’ve never seen so much inserting on a computer screen …………. ahem ….. file 25 can really take it …… whew ……. ok, pretty lame …… but I’m leaving it there. So….I, like many others above me, rushed for a separate working computer to find information on what was happening to mine. After reading a few horror stories about losing data I pulled the trigger and forced a reboot. About five minutes in I started receiving the exclamation icon in my system tray, shouting something about a “corruption of the $Extend\$Objld”….owitz. I closed it out hoping like a child that it would go away. It of course didn’t and like a grown up I did exactly what it told me to do. I scheduled a Check Disk operation and prepared to let it run its course. Incidentally I did not run it in safe mode.

As I watched the endless repetition scorch my screen, and listened to the drive do its best “nails on a chalkboard” impression I stumbled across Janos blog. I see it has brought a semblance of calm to readers since November of 06. I am grateful to all those who have contributed information, and sympathize with those who have lost some! I was lucky. I am writing this from my machine which has been spit from CHKDSK seemingly unharmed after 2 ½ hours of ……… well ….. it wasn’t that bad. I have everything backed up on an external WD 300Gig. My internal is also a WD 300Gig with 50 partitioned for XP SP3. It was the 250Gig internal partition that needed the repair.

I do have however, additional information for future reference. I was setting folder permissions for the entire f:\ drive (the 250Gig internal partition) when the power blipped from a wicked storm and shut down the machine. I am 99.7% sure, that is what caused my particular problem. Thank you Janos for keeping the thread alive.

I found this answer re the disc consistency notice on another website. I've no idea if it's valid:

This happens because during the shutdown process, the contents of the virtual cache are written to the destination device.
If device is an Integrated Drive Electronics (IDE) hard disk, data may be written to the hard disk's onboard cache but not to the disk itself. When this occurs, the data is lost from the cache when the computer turns off.

To prevent it,

1. Disable Advanced Power Management (APM) in the computer's basic input/output system (BIOS)

OR

1.Start Registry Editor ( type regedit in Run).

2.Locate and click the following key in the registry:
HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\Curr entVersion

3.On the Edit menu, point to New, and then click DWORD Value.

4.Type CacheWriteDelay to name the new value, and then press ENTER.

5.Right-click the CacheWriteDelay value, and then click Modify.

6. Under Base, click Decimal

7.In the Value data box, type 2000, and then click OK.

8.Quit Registry Editor.

Shut down and restart the computer. Permit Windows to finish running ScanDisk and wait for the Windows desktop to appear. Then, shut down and restart the computer again.

This should solve your problem.

So, visual designers, here's a list of 20 things that drive developers crazy. If you're not doing at least 15, then you're not trying hard enough.

1. Add rounded corners to every single element on the page. While you're at it, add shadows and gradients too.

2. Use the same PSD as a starting point for every project. Hide unused layers, but don't delete them. Make sure your PSD is at least 100MB.

3. Use sIFR on every piece of text. Bonus points if you choose a font that's very similar to Arial.

4. Never use the same dimensions on elements. Give each a different font size and colour (for black, use #000000, #111111, #121212 ...).

5. Use a lot of breakout images with transparency. Web developers love graphics breaking out of boxes and columns. Bonus points if you add text wrapping around images.

6. Add a modal window. At least half the site should happen in a modal window.

7. Add a Facebook Connect button. It's just a button. How hard can it be to implement?

8. Hide important PSD layers. Later, tell the developer that they missed a hidden element.

9. Create buttons with rollover, active and clicked states. Then don't tell anyone you've done this. Create a separate file for them and send it on at the last minute. We love surprises.

10. Tell the developer about some fancy functionality you read about somewhere on a blog. Then tell them to build it, because, if you saw it somewhere, clearly it's possible.

11. Add a carousel. Oh yeah, and make sure it's a full-screen carousel.

12. Use Lorem Ipsum instead of real copy. And make sure the reserved space is not big enough for real copy.

13. Randomly merge PSD layers. Why not? (But don't merge too many. It'll take you further away from the magic 100MB target).

14. Name all your files 'final', plus a date and a random letter (final-2010-12-01a.psd, final- 2010-12-01r.psd, final-2010-12-02b.psd).

15. Don't worry about making changes once everything is signed off. When we're done with a page, send another, completely different version of it. And tell us that those changes are necessary and essential for user experience.

16. Don't name or organise your PSD layers and folders.

17. If you're designing a form, forget about error and success states. We'll squeeze that stuff in somewhere. We love guessing your intentions.

18. When you're designing a website, don't invite any developers for brainstorming or design meetings. Make sure we're the last ones to see the layout. Show it to the client first, so it will be too late to introduce even a modicum of sanity into your work.

19. We should hang out more, so during QA don't use bug tracking software. Come sit with us for an entire day and point out changes you want made over our shoulders. Use the opportunity for some impromptu design updates as well.

20. And finally, this is the most important thing: don't learn anything about HTML, CSS, JavaScript or browser issues. The less you know about it, the more important we seem.

Hey there!

Restoring a dump usually means to "import", "run" or "execute" the .sql files. If you have a database manager tool (phpMyAdmin) that accepts .sql files it will most probably execute them in some way. When were talking about executing in this context it means running the commands contained in the .sql files in order on the database. Because if you open an .sql file with Notepad and take a peek you'll see that it's just a plain regular text file with SQL commands listed.

So when we're talking about restoring the files in a certain order it means that you first have to click and "run" the data structure file, because that'll create the structure (layout) of the tables and then "run" the rest of the files in order which will then fill the tables that were created in step 1 with data.

If this explanation wasn't clear enough, feel free to ask away.

والمبيد الخاص بها فشركتنا شركة الكمال لديها فريق عمل قد قام بدراسة جميع انواع الحشرات مع معرفة كيفية التعامل معها واماكن تجمعها
لتخلص منها نهائيا دون عوده مع التعامل بشكل جدى مع النمل الابيض والبق والعته لما لهم من اضرار كثيره ولا تقلق عزيزى العميل فنحن

Interesantă alegere. Vreau să zic că deși eram un fan iPhone, ști bine, am decis ca la iPhone4s să renunț la iOS și să îmi iau ceva de top cu Android dar să și îmi permit acest telefon fără eforturi financiare considerabile. Profitând de portarea mai multor numere de la orange la vodafone am primit o ofertă compatibilă cu cererile mele la un LG G3. Am studiat și am decis să îl iau. Trecerea de la iOS la Android a fost privită de ochii mei applenieni cu neîncredere și scepticism. Acum nu regret. LG G3 a fost un telefon foarte reușit din punctul meu de vedere. La cei 32Gb interni și cu un card de 16Gb nu am reușit niciodată să rămân fără spațiu. În comparație cu ce am avut a fost net superior. După 2/3 ani mă gândesc însă să îl schimb. Am încercat să văd cum ar fi să revin la iOS, dar S7 de la Samsung nu vrea să mă lase iar acum că au lansat S8 cred că în toamnă va fi momentul lui S7. Vorba ta, nu vreau să vând rinichiul încă pentru un telefon.
